As Michelle Te Rure wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/10/2004 at 19:21:27 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>In a warehouse, accidents have been taking place at the rate of 2 
>every 3 months.
>
>If a month is chosen at random, find the probability of at least 
one 
>accident.
>
>[Difficulty]
>Because we are using distributions I dont know really where to 
start?
>Im lost.
>
>[Thoughts]
>Ive chosen the Poisson distribution and have calculated the mean 
and 
>standard deviation.


The average in 1 month = 2/3

The probability of at least 1 accident in a month

        = 1 - P(no accidents)

        =  1 - e^(-2/3)

        =  1 - 0.513417

        =  0.48658


